  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering, primarily at the federal level in the United States. The key ones include:\n\n*   **The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970:** This is foundational legislation that requires financial institutions to keep records of cash transactions exceeding a certain threshold, report suspicious activity, and implement anti-money laundering programs. It is often referred to as the Currency and Foreign Transactions Reporting Act.\n\n*   **The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986:** This act made money laundering a federal crime. It prohibits individuals from engaging in financial transactions involving the proceeds of specified unlawful activity (SUA), also known as predicate offenses, with the intent to promote the activity, conceal the proceeds, or avoid transaction reporting requirements.\n\n*   **The Money Laundering Suppression Act of 1994:** This act focused on improving coordination among law enforcement agencies, clarifying the definition of money laundering, and increasing penalties.\n\n*   **The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001:** Passed in response to the September 11th attacks, this act significantly expanded the scope of anti-money laundering laws. It included provisions to:\n    *   Strengthen customer identification requirements (Know Your Customer or KYC).\n    *   Increase scrutiny of foreign financial institutions operating in the U.S.\n    *   Expand the definition of financial institutions to include a broader range of businesses.\n    *   Provide greater information sharing between law enforcement and financial institutions.\n\n*   **Title 18, U.S. Code, Section 1956 (Laundering of Monetary Instruments):** This section outlines the specific offenses related to money laundering, including engaging in financial transactions with the proceeds of unlawful activity and transporting funds across state or national borders to promote unlawful activity.\n\n*   **Title 18, U.S. Code, Section 1957 (Engaging in Monetary Transactions in Property Derived from Specified Unlawful Activity):** This section makes it illegal to engage in monetary transactions in criminally derived property that is of a value greater than $10,000.\n\nIn addition to these federal statutes, many states also have their own money laundering laws, which may mirror or supplement the federal laws.\n\nIt's important to note that anti-money laundering laws are complex and constantly evolving.",
